ition to Food Production -- t14. Agriculture, Archaeology, and Human Behavioral Ecology -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis innovative volume is the first collective effort by archaeologists and ethnographers to use concepts and models from human behavioral ecology to explore one of the most consequential transitions in human history: the origins of agriculture. Carefully balancing theory and detailed empirical study, and drawing from a series of ethnographic and archaeological case studies from eleven locations—including North and South America, Mesoamerica, Europe, the Near East, Africa, and the Pacific—the contributors to this volume examine the transition from hunting and gathering to farming and herding using a broad set of analytical models and concepts. These include diet breadth, central place foraging, ideal free distribution, discounting, risk sensitivity, population ecology, and costly signaling. An introductory chapter both charts the basics of the theory and notes areas of rapid advance in our understanding of how human subsistence systems evolve. Two concluding chapters by senior archaeologists reflect on the potential for human behavioral ecology to explain domestication and the transition from foraging to farming.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculturexOrigin. 0aAgriculture, Prehistoric. 0aHuman behavior. 0aHuman ecology. 0aHuman evolution. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aandes.  aanimal domestication.  aarabia.  aarchaeology.  aarizona.  acumberland.  adomestic animals.  aearly civilization.  aecology.  aenvironment.  afood production.  aforaging.  afremont.  ahbe.  ahighlands.  ahistory.  ahuman behavior.  ahuman behavioral ecology.